‚óè Puffer Server File Management Guide

  üì¶ Compression & Archives

  ZIP files

  # Zip a folder
  zip -r archive.zip foldername

  # Unzip
  unzip archive.zip

unzip archive.zip -d pascalvoc

  # Unzip to specific location
  unzip archive.zip -d /path/to/destination

  # List contents without extracting
  unzip -l archive.zip

  # Unzip quietly (no output)
  unzip -q archive.zip

  TAR files (most common on Linux)

  # Create tar.gz (compressed)
  tar -czf archive.tar.gz foldername

  # Extract tar.gz
  tar -xzf archive.tar.gz

  # Extract to specific location
  tar -xzf archive.tar.gz -C /path/to/destination

  # List contents
  tar -tzf archive.tar.gz

  # Create tar (no compression)
  tar -cf archive.tar foldername

  # Extract tar
  tar -xf archive.tar

  TAR flags explained:
  - c = create
  - x = extract
  - z = gzip compression
  - f = file
  - v = verbose (show progress)

  GZIP (single file compression)

  # Compress
  gzip filename

  # Decompress
  gunzip filename.gz

  üìÅ File Management Basics

  Navigate directories

  pwd                 # Print current directory
  ls                  # List files
  ls -la              # List all files with details
  cd foldername       # Change directory
  cd ..               # Go up one level
  cd ~                # Go to home directory
  cd /                # Go to root directory

  Create & Remove

  # Create
  mkdir foldername              # Create folder
  mkdir -p path/to/nested/dir   # Create nested folders
  touch filename.txt            # Create empty file

  # Remove
  rm filename                   # Remove file
  rm -rf foldername            # Remove folder and contents
  rmdir foldername             # Remove empty folder

  Copy & Move

  # Copy
  cp file.txt newfile.txt                 # Copy file
  cp -r folder1 folder2                   # Copy folder
  cp file.txt /path/to/destination/       # Copy to location

  # Move/Rename
  mv oldname.txt newname.txt              # Rename
  mv file.txt /path/to/destination/       # Move file
  mv folder1 /path/to/destination/        # Move folder

  View files

  cat file.txt        # Show entire file
  head file.txt       # Show first 10 lines
  head -n 20 file.txt # Show first 20 lines
  tail file.txt       # Show last 10 lines
  less file.txt       # View file (scrollable, press q to quit)

  Search

  # Find files by name
  find . -name "*.py"                    # Find all .py files
  find . -type f -name "model*"          # Find files starting with "model"

  # Search inside files
  grep "search_term" file.txt            # Search in file
  grep -r "search_term" foldername/      # Search recursively in folder

  File info

  ls -lh              # List with human-readable sizes
  du -sh foldername   # Folder size
  df -h               # Disk space
  wc -l file.txt      # Count lines in file

  Permissions

  chmod +x script.sh          # Make executable
  chmod 755 file.txt          # rwxr-xr-x permissions
  chown user:group file.txt   # Change owner

  Download files

  # wget
  wget https://example.com/file.zip

  # wget with custom name
  wget https://example.com/file.zip -O myfile.zip

  # curl
  curl -O https://example.com/file.zip

  üî• Useful Combos

  # Download and extract in one go
  wget https://example.com/data.tar.gz && tar -xzf data.tar.gz

  # Zip and remove original
  zip -r backup.zip myfolder && rm -rf myfolder

  # Check folder size before removing
  du -sh foldername && rm -rf foldername

  # Extract and remove archive
  unzip data.zip && rm data.zip

  # Copy with progress
  rsync -avh --progress source/ destination/

  üí° Pro Tips

  1. Use tab completion: Start typing and press Tab to autocomplete
  2. Use wildcards: rm *.txt removes all .txt files
  3. Be careful with rm -rf: No undo!
  4. Check before removing: ls foldername before rm -rf foldername
  5. Use -v for verbose: See what's happening (rm -rfv, cp -v, etc.)
